This result can conclude the ability of Fe3+ ions to quench the fluorescence emission intensity of N-CQDs, most likely by electron transfer between Fe3+ ions and N-CQDs instead of binding with the N-CQDs. Fe3+ ions had a 3d5 outer electronic configuration, partially occupying all five d orbitals. Due to the coordination interaction, they are more likely to accept the electron from N-CQDs, leading to nonradiative electron/hole recombination to fill their partially filled 3d orbitals. This mechanism may have caused the consequent fluorescence quenching [69]. The fluorescence lifetimes of N-CQDs and N-CQDs/ Fe3+ nanoparticles were determined to be 5.08 and 5.77 ns, respectively. The calculation of fluorescence attenuation life involved a double exponential fitting, detailed in Supporting Information 
                           Table S2 and Fig. 3c. Despite the addition of Fe3+ (500 μM), the fluorescence lifetime of N-CQDs remained nearly constant, suggesting the involvement of a static fluorescence quenching mechanism [70]. Additionally, we examined the UV − vis spectra of N-CQDs/ Fe3+. Fig. 7d illustrates that the UV − vis absorption spectra of N-CQDs/ Fe3+ partially overlapped with the excitation and emission spectra of N-CQDs. This overlap indicated that Fe3+ absorbed the excitation light that stimulated the N-CQD fluorescent probe, reducing fluorescence intensity without altering the fluorescence lifetime of the N-CQD fluorescent probe. Consequently, the fluorescence quenching of N-CQDs by Fe3+ is likely attributed to the internal filter effect. (Scheme 2
                           ) depicts a schematic illustration of the potential method by which Fe3+ ions could quench N-CQDs' fluorescence.
